Maybe using a fisheye lens in the nest box is overkill.
Live and learn.
Since I've already made one with a "normal" lens, I should be clearer about it.
This weekend I'll install the second completed nest box, and I'll post more information then.
Let's put it this way, in 2015 the birds had faster internet than me.
At least that's the plan for now.
Now there is a nest box that is already connected to my home's wireless network.
Another nest box will need some effort to get online.
Alright, during the day I hung up the new nest box. This is what it looks like in the garden.
But let's take a step back. "What's inside it, anyway?" seems to be a question no one has asked.
The top is an ESP32 camera board with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I took off from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box has an odd shape because the side panel of the nest box can rotate. It was like this when I bought it, and it couldn't be modified, so I had to design around this situation.
Since there is no power source in the garden, the entire device is powered by a solar panel and a 18650 lithium-ion battery with a capacity of 2600 mAh.
I didn't take photos of the battery or charger, but this is a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the nest box contains the battery.
It can operate for about four hours on a full charge.
I call this a "featured function." This way, the birds also have some private space.
Initially, I was unsure if the network in the garden was good enough to support this device. The old access points I replaced last autumn definitely wouldn't work.
But the coverage of the new access point is completely fine.
Now I won't even need to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof pointing down towards the garden.
If I build more nest boxes with cameras in the future, I might still do it. Especially in places far from the house, I might need it.
Now, the camera has gone offline for some reason I don't understand. It stopped working just one hour after sunset.
Maybe it stopped charging three hours before sunset due to insufficient light.
Maybe half a day isn't enough time for it to fully charge.
Let's see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have battery telemetry data. I might add this feature in future versions.
I think having more sensors would be helpful.
Maybe I should also add a battery, at least theoretically allowing this thing to last through the whole night.
Oh, and I need to switch to a different lens.
A fisheye lens is really overkill for this.
But I have already browsed through the parts on Digikey, so I might custom design a circuit board specifically for this situation.
Or maybe not. We'll see at that time.
And it's still offline.
Great.
According to the orientation of the solar panel installed on the house, the actual time it can receive sunlight is only about 90 minutes.
Wait another one or two hours to see if there is any activity (or lack thereof).
It is still offline.
Alas, there is really nothing that is easy.
It turns out that the 5V and GND lines on the USB-C splitter I used to connect the battery charger were printed in reverse on the silkscreen.
After swapping the lines, the charging indicator light came on.
ESP isn't coming online immediately; let's wait a few more minutes.
An hour has passed, and it's still offline.
It seems it's stuck in a reboot loop, triggering the reset function of Tasmota.
This board really sucks. I've already ordered a larger one, hoping it will solve the problem.
Take a look at what I found in my workshop.
This is a 24V solar panel. Unfortunately, the sun is too low (and there's also a tree blocking it), so as soon as I added a load, the voltage dropped almost completely.
It seems I won't know until tomorrow whether this solar panel is sufficient, or if I need the higher-performance solar panel I ordered.
The information on Amazon shows that this solar panel was bought in 2021, with a maximum output of 12V 1.2A.
So, either there's a problem with this solar panel, or there's a problem with my multimeter, or they changed the product page.
Hello everyone, there's some good news!
They changed the product page, and the one I have is broken.
Both the new and old product pages refer to it as a 12V 10W solar panel.
That's why I didn't delete the old email.
Hey, look: this thing reconnected about an hour ago, but only for about half a minute.
Maybe the solar panel charged the battery a little, just enough to run for 38 seconds. That brief period is about two hours ago.
Guess what: It's cloudy today! So I'm not sure if that (possibly broken) solar panel can generate enough power to get the job done.
Let's see.
Latest update: The new solar panel is installed and now seems to be working properly.
Maybe it will stop working once the sun sets, but let's see.
Interestingly: I'm using the ping integration in Home Assistant to monitor whether it's online.
The average round-trip time is 102 milliseconds. Not great, but not bad either.
